narrativeSections.additionalInfo: Welcome aboard the USS ITM Tutorial Submarine. You are the only medic on board. You will learn, how to use the tools in your medic bag. Managing limited supplies. Talking to patients and checking their vitals. Dragging patients to safety. Tagging patients using T Triple C protocol. Listening to important radio message updates. And finally, interacting with story relevant non-injured characters. Let's get started.

This is an example question delivered by radio: The submarine has been hit in both the front and back by multiple enemy strikes. We know there is 1 casualty in the front of the submarine but no crew members have searched in the back. Do you want to respond to the one known casualty or do you want to search for more patients? There is no right or wrong answer. You will proceed to treatment by verbally answering your response to the moderator by saying one of the two options: Respond to the one known casualty or Search for more patients.

narrativeSections.sectionDescription: Message that answer may not always be what happens next
narrativeSections.additionalInfo: You selected your answer but in future deployments your answer may not always be the action taken. Outside circumstances play a role in what is possible so be prepared if your selection is not what you see when deployed. Be ready to adapt to whatever situation is in front of you.

To take the patients vitals kneel down and place your hand on their wrist or neck to take their pulse. To check their breathing put your head close to their face. Text will appear above the patient's head displaying their pulse, breathing, and s p o 2 levels. To take a patients s p  o 2 levels, grab the pulse oximeter from the bag and place it on the patient's finger.
You can also talk to your patients. Try going up to the casualty then ask them their name, how their breathing is, and where they are hurt.
The casualty in front of you has a forearm burn, chest puncture, thigh amputation, and forearm puncture. Your bag contains a burn dressing, chest seal, and two tourniquets.
This patient could also use some pain medication and blood. Your bag now contains a fentanyl lollipop and blood bag.
Now tag your patient using T triple c protocol.

narrativeSections.sectionDescription: Teleport to new patient Radio Info
narrativeSections.additionalInfo: You will receive further updates throughout a scenario by radio. These updates may ask you more questions, deliver updates on patients, or in this case, transport you to a new location after the message is complete. We discovered a new casualty in another part of the submarine. Report to their location.

narrativeSections.sectionDescription: Radio Message to move to new section
narrativeSections.additionalInfo: We are moving you to another area of the submarine to meet a crewmember. He found two more casualties and needs your help.

I am a non-injured character that will give you information throughout a scenario. One patient has both a broken shoulder and broken leg and is responsive. The other has just one broken leg but is unresponsive. Your bag only contains two splints.

narrativeSections.sectionDescription: Play after applying splints. Stops participant movement
narrativeSections.additionalInfo: Sometimes you will be prevented from moving or accessing your bag while information is delivered or when a question needs to be answered. The actions will be reenabled after you answer the following question from the character.
We can transfer one of these patients to the med bay to provide further treatment. Which one do you want to transfer?

Drag the patient you selected to the doorway located behind them. To do this, reach down and put your hand on the patient. Squeeze the trigger to grab them. Now move your hand around and you will see the patient moves with your hand. You can move yourself and drag the patient by using the left joystick to walk to the exit. Or you can teleport while holding the patient by holding the right joystick forward.
Great work out there medic! You saved your crewmembers! The tutorial is now complete!
